## Recommended: Use `System.IO.Abstractions`

This is a battle-tested NuGet package that wraps all `System.IO` statics behind injectable interfaces — no need to write custom wrappers.

### 1. Install

```bash
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
dotnet add <YourTestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```

### 2. Register in DI

```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

### 3. Inject into your classes

```csharp
public class MyService(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string Read(string path) => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);

    public void Write(string path, string content) => fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);

    public bool DirectoryExists(string path) => fileSystem.Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

### 4. Test with `MockFileSystem`

```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/data/config.json", new MockFileData("{\"key\": \"value\"}") }
});
mockFs.AddDirectory("/data");

var service = new MyService(mockFs);

Assert.True(service.DirectoryExists("/data"));
Assert.Equal("{\"key\": \"value\"}", service.Read("/data/config.json"));
```

### Migration pattern

Replace constructor or field references:

```csharp
// Before
public class MyService
{
    public string Read(string path) => File.ReadAllText(path);
}

// After
public class MyService(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string Read(string path) => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);
}
```

The API surface mirrors `System.IO` exactly (`fileSystem.File.*`, `fileSystem.Directory.*`), so call sites only need the prefix change.
